  "prompt": "Besides platinum+rhodium for NOx reduction and platinum+palladium for CO reduction, which catalyst can be used in catalytic converters?",
  "response": "In addition to platinum, rhodium, and palladium, which are commonly used in catalytic converters for their effectiveness in reducing NOx and CO emissions, there are other catalysts and materials that can be used, though they might not be as widespread due to cost, availability, or efficiency factors. Some alternative catalysts or materials that have been researched or utilized include:\n\n1. **Cerium Oxide (Ceria):** Often used as a promoter or a component in catalytic converters. Cerium oxide can store and release oxygen, which helps enhance the oxidation of CO and hydrocarbons.\n\n2. **Copper-based Catalysts:** Copper-exchanged zeolites and copper oxide catalysts are explored mainly for their potential lower cost compared to platinum group metals, especially in lean-burn and diesel engines for NOx reduction.\n\n3. **Iron-based Catalysts:** Have been studied as potential NOx reducing agents, especially in selective catalytic reduction (SCR) systems. Iron can also be used in combination with zeolites.\n\n4. **Silver-based Catalysts:** Silver has been used in some cases for its oxidation properties and potential as an alternative for NOx reduction, particularly in low-cost applications.\n\n5. **Vanadium-based Catalysts:** Typically used in SCR systems, vanadium oxides are effective in reducing NOx emissions in diesel engines.\n\n6. **Zeolites:** Work well as support structures in combination with metal ions like copper or iron, particularly in NOx reduction in selective catalytic reduction systems.\n\n7. **Gold Catalysts:** While gold is expensive, at nanoscale, it may have unique catalytic properties, especially in selective oxidation reactions.\n\nDevelopment in catalytic technology constantly seeks more cost-effective and efficient alternatives, and research into various combinations and new materials is ongoing.",
